segments.text: I said, what are you doing up there?
I said, I'm a good idea.
He said, good.
I'll talk over it.
I canceled it.
I called him.
He said, are you going to come back?
I said, you know, I'll come back.
I'm going to break it.
I was like, what?
I had a meeting.
I had a meeting.
I had a meeting a few days ago, and it wasn't stopped, 5%.
I'm concerned about that.
I had a meeting.
I had a new governor.
Which governor was it?
I forgot his name.
It didn't happen easily.
Ben, won't pay.
Because I thought for another year after I forgot him.
And he didn't do that.
I was out.
I was back.
I broke.
When you met with Governor Daniels before he appointed you to the A&M Board,
you said that you promised him you would not vote for coeducation while he was governor.
Did he ask you any other questions?
He was not necessarily opposed to coeducation, was he?
Didn't he think it was just political?
Politically dangerous?
Had you known Governor Daniels a long time?
And you all had worked together before then?
Was it Governor Connolly that reappointed you?
Did you all have a conversation before he didn't call you up or anything or quiz you, interview you?
You had supported him.
In those 12 years,
did the governor call you during your service to talk about A&M?
Did you go to the legislature to lobby for A&M during those years?
Bill Moore, as senator, was a strong advocate for A&M.
Yes, sir.
Do you remember Brownrig Dewey, the state representative from Brazos County then?
He was a small, kind of quiet man.
But he was in the House of Representatives.
Were there any strong opponents in the legislature of coeducation?
Oh, I see.
Okay.
While you were on the board, was Mrs. Cashin still the hostess at the board house?
Shoot.
Okay.
Because I interviewed one of her sons the other day.
Jim.
And he was telling me that after his father died,
that for many years she was the hostess at the board house north of Sabeasa.
Now, when you all had board meetings, did you meet at the MSC or at the board house?
Let's see.
Let me ask about some other people.
Tiger Teague, was he a good ally for A&M?
What were his primary concerns?
What did he work hardest for, for A&M?
What about Lupo, Old Army Lou?
J.E.
Lupo that ran the store at Northgate?
He was a classmate of Mr. Rutter and Mr. Teague's, and he loaned money to students always.
Pinky Downs.
Pinky Downs?
Because you know Pinky Downs?
Yes, sir.
I remember him as a...
When I got there,
he was a kind of a frail little man,
but always had a smile,
and had lots of energy,
and was always going around shaking hands and patting people on the back.
That's right.
Sure was.
Yes, sir.
Let's see.
Mr. Zachary, as a...
I know he was a classmate.
Oh, class behind you.
When he was on the board,
was he a strong supporter of change?
No.
Oh, he was not for co-education?
No.
But he did care about A&M very deeply.
That's right.
And there...
We understand that his son may soon be appointed to the board.
Okay, good one.
Yes, sir.
Let's see.
We talked about Buck Shewitch yesterday.
When Buck was a student,
was he large in weight,
as he would later be,
or was he kind of trim?
And did... Was he a pleasant...
A pleasant friend's eye.
If you ever decide you want to sell any of your Shewitch items,
I want to bid for them,
because my wife and I knew him,
and we collect Shewitch items.
Buck was such a special guy.
He was, isn't he?
Oh, yes, yes.
Let's see.
Tom Harrington.
You knew him as a student.
What kind of student was he?
Christian.
And he was from Plano.
My earliest years,
we lived in Garland,
and when we needed anything fixed on the Farmall tractor,
we went to Plano,
because the Harrington family owned that,
and I believe a funeral home,
and I think a furniture store.
And the Harrington family was very, very good.
As time came to consider co-education
and volunteer corps,
was Dr. Harrington supportive of those changes?
Okay.
I hadn't thought about that,
that he would have to follow the board.
Let's see.
Dick Hervey,
Executive Director of the Former Students.
Was he a strong advocate for A&M?
Because you and Dick worked closely together, didn't you?
What about Buck Wirus?
He sure was.
He sure was.
The Former Students Association has been very blessed
to have such good leadership,
and now with Randy Mattson,
Randy's one of my favorites.
I met him the day that John Lindsay brought him to A&M
to try to recruit him as a student.
He's a good man.
Oh, he's a splendid man.
Track man.
Oh, in high school he was Allstate.
Then he played one year of basketball at A&M
and was very, very good.
Basically, he's a good, solid human being.
I agree.
Let's see.
You were in the Corps of Cadets.
What did you learn from that experience?
What did being in the Corps teach you?
To be on time, I guess.
To be on time.
Describe the uniforms that you all wore
when you were a student.
What did the uniforms look like then?
The student uniforms.
Was it a gray shirt then?
Button-up collar.
Did you all wear the high senior boots?
Did you call your roommates
fish old ladies then?
Did you all have a lot of slang?
Do you remember any of it?
Did the teachers,
the faculty members have nicknames then?
I guess they did.
What did you do in the Corps of Cadets?
I was a good boy.
I'd clean up the bar.
That's all I did.
It was a good one.
What were your favorite courses?
What subjects did you most enjoy at A&M?
Enjoyed all of them.
Agronomy?
I did it.
Wanted to make a hundred and you did.
What were the hardest courses for you?
The ones that you had to work the hardest?
